{"key":"post-13054078","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13054078</id>\n<content>Upside down is actually better for two reasons.&amp;nbsp; It's been shown with some species, specifically shiitake that re-orienting them for fruiting is a pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; This may or may not be the case with &lt;i&gt;P cubensis&lt;/i&gt;.&amp;nbsp; Secondly, the divot in the bottom of the cake caused by the shape of the jar makes a nice place to pile up some verm to soak during the fruiting cycle to keep the cakes hydrated.&amp;nbsp; BRF cakes are pretty small and if you have a nice pinset, they can easily dry out during the flush if you don't follow the above.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>13053756</prev>\n<first>13053395</first>\n<last>13054078</last>\n<when>1281884017</when>\n<utime>08/15/10 05:53 PM</utime>\n</post>"}